The Department of Human Settlements, Water and Sanitation has appealed with municipalities and private property owners to stop evictions during the lockdown. On Thursday, Minister of Human Settlements, Water and Sanitation Lindiwe Sisulu said she was informed of ongoing evictions during a conference meeting by leaders of community organisations and Non-Governmental Organisations. In a statement, the minister said such practices could lead to a widespread of the COVID-19 pandemic. “We implore our municipalities and private property owners to understand that preferably, the only movement of people that should occur now is through the de-densification initiative that was recently announced by my department, which is aimed at preventing densely populated settlements from being overwhelmed by COVID-19,” she said. ALSO READ: CELE: DON’T GIVE US A REASON TO ARREST YOU! Minister Sisulu said they were in the process of providing water and sanitation to informal settlements. “While it remains our responsibility as government to provide basic services to our communities, the situation we currently find ourselves in calls for us to do things differently. It is for this reason that we are appealing to borehole drilling companies across the country to extend their helping hand by drilling boreholes for communities who are in desperate need of water”, she added.